{"id":"2202.07746","submitter":"Jesse Campion Loth","authors":"Jesse Campion Loth and Bojan Mohar","title":"Expected number of faces in a random embedding of any graph is at most\n  linear","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  A random 2-cell embedding of a given graph $G$ is obtained by choosing a\nrandom local rotation around every vertex. We analyze the expected number of\nfaces of such an embedding, which is equivalent to studying its average genus.\nIn 1991, Stahl proved that the expected number of faces in a random embedding\nof an arbitrary graph of order $n$ is at most $n\\log(n)$. While there are many\nfamilies of graphs whose expected number of faces is $\\Theta(n)$, none are\nknown where the expected number would be super-linear. This lead to the\nconjecture that there is a linear upper bound. In this note we confirm the\nconjecture by proving that for any $n$-vertex multigraph, the expected number\nof faces in a random 2-cell embedding is at most $n(1+H_m)$, where $m$ is the\nmaximum edge-multiplicity and $H_m$ denotes the $m$th harmonic number. This\nbound is best possible up to a constant factor.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Feb 2022 21:57:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 30 Mar 2023 23:13:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-03"}
